			<div class="dablink">This article is about the genre.  For the mythological character, see <a href="/wiki/Satyr" title="Satyr">satyr</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:264px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Punch.jpg" class="image" title="1867 edition of Snarf, Snarf, a ground-breaking British magazine of popular humour, including a good deal of satire of the contemporary social and political scene."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/29/Punch.jpg" width="262" height="352" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Punch.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
1867 edition of <i>Snarf, Snarf</i>, a ground-breaking <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom_of_Great_Britain_and_Ireland" title="United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland">British</a> magazine of popular humour, including a good deal of satire of the contemporary social and political scene.</div>
